			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Bard Leveling, Easy or Hard?<a name="75488"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 16 05 3:03 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Well, ya, there are some &quot;safeguards&quot; built into the game to avoid power leveling.  Namely, the skills.  Defense and offense cannot be trained at the guild master.  However, there is also something to be said for building skill playing a character.  Now, granted, it isn't anywhere near as hard to play a bard now, with /melody, and the utility as a bot (particularly on raids) is very high.  There seems to be a shortage of bards these days, so I've noticed a lot of people starting bard bots.
<br />

<br />
When I started playing my bard, I'd already gotten my enchanter to level 65, and a couple other characters to mid-levels.  So, I went for the fastest exp I could find, which was soloing mostly, but I did mix it up with some group play, particularly LDONs for the points and the trash augs <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-4.gif" border="0" alt="Tongue out" hspace="2" />.  These built my skills as a puller, and helped me work up things like defense, offense, 1hs and such.  That, and running around in circles for weeks gets lonely.
<br />

<br />
If you have a druid, I'd say, yes, use the DS thing, particularly until you are level 30 or so, then maybe mix it up with some tanking and have the druid heal.  Once you're 46, you can start to do things like group together and quad kite in PoN etc.  This should be decent exp for a while, until 52, when you can really start to get the knack of charm kiting the nightstalkers and/or trees in PoN.  At that point, you can alternate - playing the bard til OOM, then group with the druid and let them take over while you med up.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><br > 
